Potential impacts include accidental spills, contamination by drilling-related effluents and discharges, vessels anchoring when placing pipelines, drilling rigs and production platforms, seismic exploration, use of chemical dispersants in oil spill mitigation, and platform removal.
excellent health.
Many scientists consider reef systems in Florida and the U.S. Caribbean to be in the poorest condition, mostly because they are close to dense populations and have been repeatedly hit by a series of hurricanes, diseases, and various chronic human-induced impacts.
Pacific reefs, even around urbanized islands, are in significantly better condition.
This is due in large part to the fact that many lie off isolated islands and atolls and are surrounded by deep water with prevailing strong currents, upwelling, high waves, and tropical storms that flush the reefs with clean, cool water.
